metadata.name: Ir/rational Beauty #190
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. www.tribute-hwf.com

"Since the classical age of Greece, the golden ratio has been well known as the most balanced and therefore most aesthetically perfect proportion. In fact, it is supposedly often found in the fine arts and architecture and it is certainly important in geometry. But where is the proof that it is really the most beautiful proportion?

"The computer is proving to be a useful tool in exact art theory. Works of computer art are produced with the help of programs that describe the logic of the construction and its relevant measures. By varying the parameters you can vary the shapes of objects, and on the basis of the reaction of the public you can determine the best option. So it is possible to find valid rules to design works of art.

"A statistical evaluation would be interesting. Please email me with your results for the optimal proportion."

I found it heartwarming that in 2011, Herbert W. Franke wrote the above, accompanied with a simple functional program on a Wolfram Demonstration page (https://demonstrations.wolfram.com/IsTheGoldenRatioReallyTheMostBeautifulProportion/) titled 'Is the Golden Ratio Really the Most Beautiful Proportion?' and invited people to submit their findings to him.

The main idea behind this project is ratios, a variety of them, used in a variety of ways, such as how a rectangle is repeatedly subdivided, or how it influences the aspect ratio of the piece, or how the colors in a palette are selected. These are represented in various styles, some of which are inspired by the aesthetic of Herbert W. Franke's diverse artworks, and his openness to experimentation with new technologies, such as plotter drawings, screens, screenprints, or 2D and 3D digital renderings.

This project, while not designed to be a formal statistical evaluation, is but my fun, colorful, and humble response to your inquiry, dear Herbert.

---

25% of primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke, with the goal of raising 20,000 Euros so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any money raised beyond this goal will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

---

Controls:
• Double-click/tap or 'R' reassembles the piece (This automatically happens every minute)

Note: Some mints require WEBGL and/or may take several seconds to fully render.

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #215
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Rose 1851 #12
metadata.description:
In this 100% code generated bloom project, I made many new attempts to combine photography elements into generative art.

First at all, I love the images of early wet plate collodion photography (published in 1851 by Frederick Scott Archer), so I tried to make these artworks look similar.

To have the image more photography aesthetic, depth of field is an important factor. I put lots of effort into making it fully present in these images.

Furthermore, I think these days few have an experience of darkroom processes, therefore I also tried to make an algorithm of animations to simulation the developing process that darkroom workers are obsessed with.

And finally, the most important thing, why I chose rose as the protagonist? The answer is pretty simple, because I want to present these artworks of 99 roses to my dear wife.

Made with p5.js/WebGL.

Note: the frame of the image might be different for different GPU system.

metadata.name: Colored Elementary Cellular Automaton #8
metadata.description:
The algorithm is based on Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton. 
This is a 1D cellular automaton with a neighborhood of 5 cells. This gives us 2^5 = 32 patterns for a neighborhood and 2^32 = 4.29B possible combinations!!! The size of the cell varies in a range of 2 to 8. There is a 15% of getting a black and white art.

Pattern rarity:
- Pattern 1 _25%
- Pattern 2 _30%
- Pattern 3 _35%
- Pattern 4 _15%

Note: The art might look in different resolutions because of the responsive view, but the color, pattern, and layout remain the same.

metadata.name: NEBULAE #95
metadata.description:
NEBULAE invites you to deep space exploration to search for rare nebulas. As a space explorer you will most likely encounter an NGC, the common nebula type, but on your travels there is an possibility you will witness the powerful creative forces of the universe.. or discover something even more magical.

This project was created with randomly generated Embergen particle simulations combined with cables.gl background setup. I want to deeply thank Murat Atimtay for all the help with this first generative mint and VerticalCryptoArt & somaticbits for their helpful resources.


[e] save as png

I hope this series sparks your imagination and love for color as it did for me.

- Walt

metadata.name: Abstract Calligraphy #77
metadata.description:
This work is inspired by Japanese avant-garde calligraphy (前衛書 Zenei-sho, or 墨象 Boku-shou). After World War II, the art of Japanese calligraphy was rapidly modernized. The ultimate result was avant-garde calligraphy that did not depict characters. They resembled the works of contemporary Western paintings of the same period, such as Abstract Expressionism and Art informel. In fact, some of the avant-garde calligraphy works were drawn with oil paint on canvas instead of Sumi ink on paper. So what is the difference between painting and calligraphy in those works?
A founder of avant-garde calligraphy said that the artistic essence of calligraphy art lies in the expression of a well-honed brushstroke, so the materials used are merely a medium. Then, is it possible for computer-drawn Bezier curves to become calligraphy art? This is an experiment in that.

This work is interactive. Clicking on the image or pressing the "m" key on the keyboard will randomly transform the shape of the strokes. There are 10 types of brushes. You can switch to other brushes by pressing the number keys on the keyboard (Touch devices switch with the direction of the swipe).
In addition, the strokes resize responsively to the window size, but the shape of the brush remains the same, so you can enjoy a different look by changing the screen's aspect ratio.
